A linear regression of one dependent variable, y, and one independent variable, x, will model the linear relationship between x and y given a set of data points. One way to tune the parameters of a linear regression is the "ordinary least squares method." In this method, each observation, yi, is compared to the regression's prediction, ŷi, at that point, xi. The difference between these values (i.e., the error) is squared for each data point, and the regression parameters are tuned to minimize the sum of those squared errors. 

Task

We would like you to write a program that determines the slope, m, and intercept, b, of a line generated by fitting a linear regression to a set of data points using the "ordinary least squares method." Your program will be provided N coordinates, in the form of pairs of numbers. These numbers will represent x and y. For each data point, the first number represents x and the second number represents y.

Input Format

The first line contains N, the number of coordinate pairs.

The next N lines will contain two numbers separated by a space, xi and yi. These floating point numbers will represent coordinates to be fitted in the x-y plane. The first number of each pair is the x-value of the coordinate. The second number is the y-value.

Constraints

1 < N < 1000

Not all xi will be identical.

Example Input:

4
4.377277 15.872122
7.853586 40.462923
7.799758 34.224711
2.725926 12.91376

Output Format

Print the slope, m, and intercept, b, rounded to the 3rd decimal place and formatted as follows:

m = 5.128
b = -3.308

Note: output must follow the format above, with two lines of printed text, starting with m =  and b =  in that order.
